              <div class="article_col-main article_col-main-left article_main">
                <div class="article-body">
                      <p> The 91st Academy Awards was a night filled with historic wins for diversity and representation. The biggest award of the night went to "Green Book" for best picture — edging out top competitors like “Roma” and “Black Panther." Catch up on what went down in our posts below, and <a href="https://www.nbcnews.com/pop-culture/awards/who-won-oscars-full-list-nominees-winners-n971796" target="_blank"><strong>see the complete list of Oscar winners here!</strong></a> </p>
                  
                        <div class="widget widget_max-article">
                          
                        </div>
                          <div class="liveblog" data-liveblog-channel="oscars-2019">
                  <div class="hub-header_sub-header" itemprop="headline">
                      <h2>Reel Talk</h2>
                  </div>
                  <div class="liveblog_bt-new-post-wrapper">
                    <button class="btn btn_liveblog liveblog_bt-new-post is-hidden" style="position: static"></button>
                  </div>
                    <div class="liveblog_post nbcnews-dc-liveblog" data-liveblog-post-id="" data-liveblog-post-created="2019-02-25T04:25:00.000Z" data-liveblog-post-updated="2019-02-25T04:25:00.000Z">
                      <div class="liveblog_post-header">
                        <div class="liveblog_byline-meta-wrapper">
                            <span class="byline byline_liveblog">Ethan Sacks</span>
                          <time class="liveblog_byline-timestamp timestamp_liveblog js-timeago" itemprop="datePublished" datetime="2019-02-25T04:25:00.000Z" content="2019-02-25T04:25:00.000Z">5 days ago</time>
                        </div>
                      </div>
                          <header class="nbcnews-dc-header cf">
                            <h2 class="nbcnews-dc-heading"><a href="https://www.nbcnews.com/card/even-without-host-oscars-telecast-can-t-end-time-n975536">Even without a host, Oscars telecast can&#x27;t end on time</a></h2>
                          </header>
                      <div itemprop="articleBody">
                                          <p> Time still wasn't on Oscar producers' side. </p>
                                          <p> Sunday night's telecast, the first since 1989 to go without a host, still couldn't wrap up in under three hours — the scheduled running time so important to the show's network host, ABC. </p>
                                          <p> That the show ended just 18 minutes late is still a remarkable accomplishment after the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences had to backtrack on an unpopular attempt to scale back by cutting four of the less-glamorous categories from the live telecast.The dubious record for longest telecast is held by the 2002 Academy Awards, which lasted four hours and 23 minutes. Of course, the record is still held by the very first Oscars in 1929, hosted by Douglas Fairbanks, which lasted a reported 15 minutes. </p>
                                          <p> The telecast has lasted longer than three hours consistently since the Oscars first broke that mark in 1974.   </p>
                                              <section class="nbcnews-dc-section">
                                                  <figure class="nbcnews-dc-embed_graphic">
                                                      <noscript><img class="img-responsive img_inline" src="https://media1.s-nbcnews.com/j/newscms/2019_08/2763936/190224-lady-gaga-bradley-cooper-oscars-piano-ac-1041p_a4da111c881716d171a4fff4241c29d9.nbcnews-ux-600-480.jpg"
                                                                     alt="Image: Lady Gaga, Bradley Cooper, 91st Academy Awards -  Oscars - Hollywood" title="" itemprop="image"/></noscript>
                                              
                                                      <a href="https://media1.s-nbcnews.com/j/newscms/2019_08/2763936/190224-lady-gaga-bradley-cooper-oscars-piano-ac-1041p_a4da111c881716d171a4fff4241c29d9.nbcnews-ux-2880-1000.jpg" class="js-lightbox lightbox_link">
                                                          <button class="btn btn_overlay"><i class="fa fa-expand"></i></button>
                                                          <img class="js-lazy img-responsive img_inline"
                                                               src="https://nodeassets.nbcnews.com/images/transparent-placeholder.gif"
                                                               data-original="https://media1.s-nbcnews.com/j/newscms/2019_08/2763936/190224-lady-gaga-bradley-cooper-oscars-piano-ac-1041p_a4da111c881716d171a4fff4241c29d9.nbcnews-ux-600-480.jpg" alt="Image: Lady Gaga, Bradley Cooper, 91st Academy Awards -  Oscars - Hollywood" title=""/>
                                                      </a>
                                              
                                                      <div class="js-caption_wrapper">
                                                              <figcaption class="img-caption img-caption_default">
                                                        <span class="img-caption_txt">
                                                                Lady Gaga and Bradley Cooper perform &quot;Shallow&quot; from &quot;A Star Is Born&quot; during the 91st Academy Awards in Los Angeles on Feb. 24, 2019.</span>
                                                                <i class="fa fa-camera" aria-hidden="true"></i>
                                                                Mike Blake
                                                            
                                                                / Reuters
                                                              </figcaption>
                                                      </div>
                                                  </figure>
                                              </section>
